 all different gifts, and it's wasteful to tell half the population their gifts don't belong in certain places. The way I see it, we're missing out on solutions to problems because we're not letting everyone contribute. In my work, I've seen how diversity actually makes teams stronger. Different people see different problems and come up with different solutions. How do we fix it? Start young. Let girls take things apart and put them back together. Stop treating science and math like they're for boys only. Create mentorship programs where women in technical fields can guide younger women. I wish I'd had more support when I was starting out. Make workplaces more flexible so women with families can participate fully. And honestly, just stop being surprised when a woman shows up ready to do technical work. Treat it as normal, because it should be. We need practical changes, not just talk. The church communities I'm part of could do more to encourage young women too. It's about changing hearts and minds, one person at a time, until nobody blinks when a woman walks into a lab or picks up a wrench.","reasoning_summary":"The persona is a 63-year-old female electrician with no formal education who immigrated to the US and has worked in a male-dominated technical field. Her direct experience in a trade gives her authentic insight into gender barriers in technical fields including science. Her moderate openness and conscientiousness suggest she values practical solutions and steady approaches. Low extraversion indicates a more reserved, observational tone rather than passionate advocacy. Her Christian beliefs and experience raising four children inform her views on equality and potential. Her lack of formal education but successful career demonstrates learning through experience. The depression and immigrant background suggest resilience but also awareness of struggles. Her moderate agreeableness means she'll be balanced rather than confrontational. The response should reflect